AGI - "Around antifascism is possible and necessary popular unity". Sergio Mattarella uses Aldo Moro's words, killed by the Red Brigades in 1978, to explain how antifascism is a duty. And to celebrate 25 April, while in the political world some distinctions continue, the President clearly recalls the fundamentals of the Republic: "The 25th of April is a fundamental event for Italy: the feast of peace, freedom found, and the return to the nous of democratic nations. That peace and freedom which, by finding roots in the resistance of a people against Nazi barbarism, have produced the Republican Constitution, in which everyone can recognize himself, and which represents a guarantee of democracy and justice, of denial of any form or principle of authoritarianism or totalitarianism". A civil base to look at the future, which is based on a memory made of clear historical data, already in the past the President condemned every revisionism: the Nazism perpetuated over 5000 eccidi, with a " fascist propaganda that denied the undeniable", with a regime that had a face from the "brutali and disumani" traits.
&nbsp;
After laying a crown at the Altar of the Homeland with the premier Giorgia Meloni and the presidents of Senate and Chamber Ignazio The Russian and Lorenzo Fontana, Mattarella celebrates the Liberation Day in Civitella in Val di Chiana. "I have come here today, one of the symbolic places of Nazi barbarism, to commemorate all the victims of war crimes, committed in that 1944, on national territory and abroad" because "it is necessary, today and in the future, to remember those massacres and those victims. Without memory, there is no future."
&nbsp;
And then the memory needs first of all unobtainable historical data. "The military judiciary and historians, after a difficult research work, lasted decades, have, so far, documented on the Italian territory five thousand cruel and infamous episodes of eccidi, reprisals, summary executions". A Nazi-fascist strategy to "make land burned around the partisans", "it was a serious crime of war, contrary to any international rule and military honor and, more so, to the principles of humanity". And again: "The infamy of the Marzabotto massacre, the greatest accomplishment in Italy, followed an equally unworthy corollary: the fascist propaganda, in the newspapers subjected to controls and censures, denied the undeniable, trying to deny the incident". But "totally submissive to Hitler's imperialist Germany, fascist Italy, entered the conflict without any respect for soldiers sent to die cynically, would not have had any escape." &nbsp;
&nbsp;
During the war the Italians changed judgment on fascism: "In the disastrous retreat of Russia, on the camps of El Alamein, in the brutal repressions carried out in Greece, in the Balkans, in Ethiopia, in the deportations of the Jews to the fields of extermination, in the support of the Nazis in the repression of the civilian population, the break between the Italian people and fascism," which "had long discovered his face, revealing his true brutal and inhuman traits".
&nbsp;
On September 8, the country was in absolute chaos. "But many Italians did not bow to dishonour. They chose the ransom route. A moral ransom, even before politicians," the President is still rebuilding. "The Resistance was born, a movement that, in its plurality of persons, motivations, proceeds and ideal thrusts, found its unity in the need to end Nazi rule on Italian territory, to establish a new cohabitation, founded on law and peace." A people made up of war veterans and young fans, peasants and intellectuals, monarchists and Republicans, joined "to fight, with weapons, against oppression and invader".
&nbsp;
The civilians joined the military. "There was the heroic Resistance of the approximately 600 thousand soldiers who, after September 8, refused to serve the Republic of Salò, the puppet regime established by Mussolini under the total control of Hitler. They passed for the weapons and deported, "50,000 died in the detention camps in Germany." Then there was "the Resistance of the populations, rebelled spontaneously" and "the courageous labor struggles". A real "Civil Resis, without arms, a wide and widespread movement, which also saw the rebirth of women's protagonism, finally subtracted from the subordinate role" which directed fascism with an ideology in which "Pity was not expected". The turn was net: "The Resistance, in its so different forms, contributed greatly to the advancement of the Allies and the defeat of Nazi fascism."
&nbsp;
Italy then freed itself "from the occupying Nazi, from a terrible war, but also from a ruthless dictatorship that, along the span of twenty years, had suffocated political and civil rights, trampled fundamental freedoms, persecuted Jews and minorities, educated young people to the sacrilege religion of violence and abuse. The entry into the war, alongside Hitler, was the direct and inevitable consequence of this climate of fanatical exaltation ".
&nbsp;
